  "response": "There are numerous legal precedents related to money laundering cases across different jurisdictions. Some key cases include:\n\n1. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Major international bank convicted of widespread money laundering\n- Significant case establishing complex financial institution liability\n\n2. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Supreme Court case defining money laundering statutory interpretation\n- Clarified understanding of proceeds and financial transactions\n\n3. R v. Anwoir (UK, 2008)\n- Established knowledge requirements in money laundering prosecutions\n- Defined standard of proof for criminal intent\n\n4. Van Wyk v. Turner (South Africa, 2003)\n- Important precedent regarding international money laundering investigations\n- Addressed cross-border financial crime frameworks\n\nThese cases generally establish principles regarding:\n- Proof of criminal intent\n- Financial institution responsibilities\n- Evidence standards\n- Jurisdictional reach of anti-money laundering laws\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?\n\nNote: I aim to provide factual legal information without offering specific legal advice.",
